00:08:02,440 --> 00:08:07,000
The jury has to decide, is the defendant innocent or guilty?
陪审团必须决定，被告是有罪还是无罪？

172
00:08:07,000 --> 00:08:08,000
Okay.
好的。

173
00:08:08,000 --> 00:08:09,320
These are two important adjectives.
这是两个重要的形容词。

174
00:08:09,320 --> 00:08:10,320
Innocent.
无辜的。

175
00:08:10,320 --> 00:08:11,320
What does this mean?
这是什么意思？

176
00:08:11,320 --> 00:08:14,120
So if he is innocent, that means he did not commit the crime.
如果他无辜，那就意味着他没有犯罪。

177
00:08:14,120 --> 00:08:16,600
He is not responsible for what happened.
他对发生的事情不负责任。

178
00:08:16,600 --> 00:08:18,160
He did not steal the wallets.
他没有偷钱包。

179
00:08:18,160 --> 00:08:19,160
Okay.
好的。

180
00:08:19,160 --> 00:08:20,920
So we often say babies are so innocent.
所以我们常说婴儿很天真。

181
00:08:20,920 --> 00:08:21,920
Right.
对。

182
00:08:21,920 --> 00:08:22,920
They can't do anything.
他们什么坏事都做不了。

183
00:08:22,920 --> 00:08:23,920
They can't do anything wrong.
他们不会做错事。

184
00:08:23,920 --> 00:08:24,920
Right.
对。

185
00:08:24,920 --> 00:08:26,400
So guilty would be the opposite.
所以有罪就是反义词。

186
00:08:26,400 --> 00:08:27,400
That's right.
没错。

187
00:08:27,400 --> 00:08:34,840
So usually when someone is guilty, they're sad, they feel bad, you want them to pay you.
通常当一个人有罪时，他们会难过、感到愧疚，你希望他们赔偿你。

188
00:08:34,840 --> 00:08:35,840
And they go to jail.
然后他们进监狱。

189
00:08:35,840 --> 00:08:36,840
Yeah.
是的。

190
00:08:36,840 --> 00:08:38,640
In bad situations, they go to jail.
在糟糕的情况下，他们会进监狱。

191
00:08:38,640 --> 00:08:40,840
If you burn down my house, of course you're going to go to jail.
如果你烧了我的房子，你当然要进监狱。

192
00:08:40,840 --> 00:08:41,840
Right.
对。

193
00:08:41,840 --> 00:08:42,840
All right.
好的。

194
00:08:42,840 --> 00:08:43,840
So guilty means you did a crime.
所以有罪意味着你犯了罪。

195
00:08:43,840 --> 00:08:45,440
You did a bad thing.
你做了坏事。

196
00:08:45,440 --> 00:08:49,880
So we talked about the prosecution and the defense of the defendant.
我们谈到了控方和辩方对被告的辩护。

197
00:08:49,880 --> 00:08:55,320
And what happens is they also present some key elements that will prove if the person
然后他们会提出一些关键要素，来证明这个人

198
00:08:55,320 --> 00:08:56,960
is innocent or guilty.
是有罪还是无罪。

199
00:08:56,960 --> 00:08:59,560
And those elements are called evidence.
这些要素被称为证据。

200
00:08:59,560 --> 00:09:00,560
That's right.
没错。

201
00:09:00,560 --> 00:09:02,480
So back to this idea, we tell a story.
回到这个想法，我们讲述一个故事。

202
00:09:02,480 --> 00:09:04,240
Maybe a witness can help us tell our story.
也许证人可以帮助我们讲述故事。

203
00:09:04,240 --> 00:09:07,160
But as you say, evidence is stuff.
但正如你所说，证据是实物。

204
00:09:07,160 --> 00:09:08,200
It's things.
是具体的东西。

205
00:09:08,200 --> 00:09:13,280
So in the case of the house, I could say you have matches and you smell like smoke and
所以在房子这个案例中，我可以说你有火柴，而且你身上有烟和油的味道。

206
00:09:13,280 --> 00:09:14,280
oil.


207
00:09:14,280 --> 00:09:17,440
This is evidence for me to use to show that you are guilty.
这就是我用来证明你有罪的证据。

208
00:09:17,440 --> 00:09:18,440
Right.
对。

209
00:09:18,440 --> 00:09:20,520
So in this case, do we have any evidence?
那么在这个案例中，我们有证据吗？

210
00:09:20,520 --> 00:09:23,720
There's no evidence, says the defendant.
被告说，没有证据。

211
00:09:23,720 --> 00:09:24,720
Right.
对。

212
00:09:24,720 --> 00:09:25,720
All right.
好的。

213
00:09:25,720 --> 00:09:26,720
So evidence is proof.
所以证据就是证明。

214
00:09:26,720 --> 00:09:28,400
It's physical proof.
是实物证明。

215
00:09:28,400 --> 00:09:29,400
Yeah.
是的。

216
00:09:29,400 --> 00:09:33,640
And most of the times when you see movies or TV shows, they will find, I don't know,
大多数时候，你在电影或电视节目里看到，他们会找到，比如，

217
00:09:33,640 --> 00:09:38,240
like maybe a fingerprint that's evidence or somebody's glasses.
指纹作为证据，或者某人的眼镜。

218
00:09:38,240 --> 00:09:39,240
A cell phone.
一部手机。

219
00:09:39,240 --> 00:09:40,240
Exactly.
没错。

220
00:09:40,240 --> 00:09:41,240
All right.
好的。

221
00:09:41,240 --> 00:09:42,240
So evidence.
所以证据。

222
00:09:42,240 --> 00:09:43,960
This is very important when you want to build a case.
这在构建案件时非常重要。

223
00:09:43,960 --> 00:09:47,160
Finally, at the end of a trial, we have a verdict.
最后，在审判结束时，我们会有裁决。

224
00:09:47,160 --> 00:09:49,320
Now, what is a verdict?
那么，什么是裁决？

225
00:09:49,320 --> 00:09:55,000
Well a verdict is a final decision or a conclusion in which the jury says, yeah, the person is
裁决是陪审团做出的最终决定或结论，说，是的，这个人

226
00:09:55,000 --> 00:09:57,960
guilty or he's not guilty, he's innocent.
有罪，或者他无罪，他是无辜的。

227
00:09:57,960 --> 00:10:01,360
So we use this word usually to reach a verdict.
所以我们通常用这个词来说“达成裁决”。

228
00:10:01,360 --> 00:10:03,480
The jury reaches a verdict.
陪审团达成裁决。

229
00:10:03,480 --> 00:10:07,760
Now it's interesting why we say to reach because a jury is not just one person.
有趣的是为什么我们说“达成”，因为陪审团不是一个人。

230
00:10:07,760 --> 00:10:09,520
A jury is many people.
陪审团是很多人。

231
00:10:09,520 --> 00:10:12,080
And so these people have to decide together.
所以这些人必须一起决定。

232
00:10:12,080 --> 00:10:13,220
They have to argue.
他们必须争论。

233
00:10:13,220 --> 00:10:16,520
They have to make a conclusion that everyone agrees on.
他们必须达成一个所有人都同意的结论。

234
00:10:16,520 --> 00:10:21,720
And this is to reach a conclusion, to reach a verdict because they have to travel there.
这就是“达成结论”、“达成裁决”，因为他们需要一起努力

235
00:10:21,720 --> 00:10:23,880
They have to go together and figure it out.
去弄清楚。

236
00:10:23,880 --> 00:10:24,880
Right.
对。

237
00:10:24,880 --> 00:10:25,880
That's very, very important.
这非常重要。

238
00:10:25,880 --> 00:10:29,220
So the jury reaches a verdict.
所以陪审团达成裁决。

239
00:10:29,220 --> 00:10:31,440
And we did have one other phrase that's very interesting.
我们还有一个非常有趣的短语。

240
00:10:31,440 --> 00:10:33,520
It doesn't quite fit with the other ones.
它和其他词不太一样。

241
00:10:33,520 --> 00:10:36,520
We heard this phrase from the defendant.
我们从被告那里听到了这个短语。

242
00:10:36,520 --> 00:10:41,680
The lawyer says, so these so-called witnesses didn't actually see anything.
律师说，这些所谓的证人实际上什么也没看到。

243
00:10:41,680 --> 00:10:43,800
What is so-called?
“所谓的”是什么意思？

244
00:10:43,800 --> 00:10:48,440
So he's being sarcastic when he uses this phrase, so-called, right?
所以他用“所谓的”这个短语时是在讽刺，对吧？

245
00:10:48,440 --> 00:10:52,760
That's why even his tone changes, these so-called witnesses.
这就是为什么他的语气都变了，这些所谓的证人。

246
00:10:52,760 --> 00:10:55,880
So it's a way of expressing sarcasm.
所以这是一种表达讽刺的方式。

247
00:10:55,880 --> 00:11:00,440
He's saying they say they're witnesses, but they're not really because they didn't see
他在说他们自称是证人，但实际上不是，因为他们没看到

248
00:11:00,440 --> 00:11:01,440
anything.
任何东西。

249
00:11:01,440 --> 00:11:02,440
Right.
对。

250
00:11:02,440 --> 00:11:04,600
So so-called means you say that they are, but they're not really.
所以“所谓的”意思是你说他们是，但他们实际上不是。

251
00:11:04,600 --> 00:11:05,600
Right.
对。

252
00:11:05,600 --> 00:11:09,960
I could also say, your so-called lawyer thinks he can help you, but he can't.
我也可以说，你所谓的律师以为他能帮你，但他帮不了。

253
00:11:09,960 --> 00:11:10,960
Right.
对。

254
00:11:10,960 --> 00:11:12,940
That means I don't think your lawyer is very good.
那意味着我认为你的律师不怎么样。

255
00:11:12,940 --> 00:11:14,400
I don't think he's a real lawyer.
我不认为他是个真正的律师。

256
00:11:14,400 --> 00:11:15,400
Right.
对。

257
00:11:15,400 --> 00:11:18,840
Or sometimes people say, my so-called friend stood me up last night.
或者有时人们会说，我所谓的朋友昨晚放我鸽子了。

258
00:11:18,840 --> 00:11:20,640
Oh, so it's not really a friend.
哦，所以那不算真正的朋友。

259
00:11:20,640 --> 00:11:21,640
He's not really a friend.
他不是真正的朋友。

260
00:11:21,640 --> 00:11:22,640
Exactly.
没错。

261
00:11:22,640 --> 00:11:23,640
So-called.
所谓的。

262
00:11:23,640 --> 00:11:24,640
All right.
好了。

263
00:11:24,640 --> 00:11:25,640
That's another good one.
这又是一个好词。

264
00:11:25,640 --> 00:11:27,000
Let's listen to this dialogue one more time.
让我们再听一遍这段对话。

265
00:11:27,000 --> 00:11:37,040
Really think about some of the words you heard today, and we'll be back in a moment.
认真想想你今天听到的一些词，我们一会儿回来。

266
00:11:37,040 --> 00:11:40,840
Your Honor, ladies and gentlemen of the jury.
法官大人，陪审团的女士们先生们。

267
00:11:40,840 --> 00:11:45,560
My client, Robert Malone, has been accused of a crime he did not commit.
我的当事人罗伯特·马龙被指控犯了一项他没有犯的罪行。

268
00:11:45,560 --> 00:11:49,040
The prosecution has accused my client of being a pickpocket.
控方指控我的当事人是个扒手。

269
00:11:49,040 --> 00:11:53,240
I know we have heard the testimony of many people here today.
我知道我们今天听到了很多人的证词。

270
00:11:53,240 --> 00:11:57,000
People who claim the defendant, my client, stole their wallets.
那些声称被告，也就是我的当事人，偷了他们钱包的人。

271
00:11:57,000 --> 00:11:59,000
I feel sorry for these victims.
我为这些受害者感到难过。

272
00:11:59,000 --> 00:12:00,800
I really do.
我真的很难过。

273
00:12:00,800 --> 00:12:05,180
But my client is innocent.
但我的当事人是无辜的。

274
00:12:05,180 --> 00:12:06,920
Let's look at the facts.
让我们看看事实。

275
00:12:06,920 --> 00:12:15,400
Number one, these so-called witnesses did not actually see the defendant steal anything.
第一，这些所谓的证人并没有亲眼看到被告偷任何东西。

276
00:12:15,400 --> 00:12:21,160
Number two, when the police stopped him, he did not have any of the stolen wallets.
第二，当警察拦住他时，他身上没有任何被偷的钱包。

277
00:12:21,160 --> 00:12:23,760
There is no evidence.
没有证据。

278
00:12:23,760 --> 00:12:28,680
Therefore, ladies and gentlemen of the jury, I ask you to think carefully before giving
因此，陪审团的女士们先生们，我请你们在做出

279
00:12:28,680 --> 00:12:30,060
your verdict.
裁决之前仔细思考。

280
00:12:30,060 --> 00:12:31,520
Look at the facts.
看看事实。

281
00:12:31,520 --> 00:12:33,560
Look at the evidence.
看看证据。

282
00:12:33,560 --> 00:12:38,240
My client is innocent.
我的当事人是无辜的。

283
00:12:38,240 --> 00:12:41,320
Ladies and gentlemen of the jury, have you reached a verdict?
陪审团的女士们先生们，你们达成裁决了吗？

284
00:12:41,320 --> 00:12:43,040
Yes, Your Honor.
是的，法官大人。

285
00:12:43,040 --> 00:12:46,640
Our verdict is not guilty.
我们的裁决是无罪。

286
00:12:46,640 --> 00:12:48,020
Thank you so much.
非常感谢。

287
00:12:48,020 --> 00:12:49,020
You were great.
你太棒了。

288
00:12:49,020 --> 00:12:51,440
Thank you for all your hard work.
感谢你的辛勤工作。

289
00:12:51,440 --> 00:12:52,520
You're welcome, Robert.
不客气，罗伯特。

290
00:12:52,520 --> 00:12:55,340
I knew you were innocent, so my job was easy.
我知道你是无辜的，所以我的工作很容易。

291
00:12:55,340 --> 00:12:57,400
Take care of yourself, okay?
照顾好自己，好吗？

292
00:12:57,400 --> 00:13:00,000
Thanks once again.
再次感谢。

293
00:13:00,000 --> 00:13:03,520
Hey, where's my wallet?
嘿，我的钱包呢？

294
00:13:03,520 --> 00:13:10,280
All right, we're back.
好了，我们回来了。

295
00:13:10,280 --> 00:13:14,500
So now a very interesting situation with the courtroom dramas.
所以现在法庭剧里出现了一个非常有趣的情况。

296
00:13:14,500 --> 00:13:18,520
And I've heard that all the people in the jury have to agree in order for them to reach
我听说陪审团的所有人都必须同意才能达成

297
00:13:18,520 --> 00:13:19,520
a verdict, right?
裁决，对吧？

298
00:13:19,520 --> 00:13:25,280
So if one of them is not convinced that the person is, for example, guilty, then they
所以如果其中一个人没有被说服，比如认为有罪，那么他们

299
00:13:25,280 --> 00:13:27,280
have to keep on deliberating.
就得继续审议。

300
00:13:27,280 --> 00:13:28,280
That's the word, right?
是这个词，对吧？

301
00:13:28,280 --> 00:13:29,280
That's right.
没错。

302
00:13:29,280 --> 00:13:32,500
So basically, the jury is always alone in a room.
所以基本上，陪审团总是单独待在一个房间里。

303
00:13:32,500 --> 00:13:38,360
Maybe they have a guard, but they're not supposed to talk to journalists or friends of the defendant
也许有个警卫，但他们不应该和记者或被告的朋友

304
00:13:38,360 --> 00:13:41,880
or anyone because their decision is supposed to be pure.
或任何人交谈，因为他们的决定应该是纯粹的。

305
00:13:41,880 --> 00:13:45,000
So they talk, and sometimes it takes 10 minutes.
所以他们讨论，有时只需要10分钟。

306
00:13:45,000 --> 00:13:48,840
Everyone agrees this person is guilty or this person is innocent.
每个人都同意这个人有罪或这个人无罪。

307
00:13:48,840 --> 00:13:49,960
But sometimes they don't agree.
但有时他们意见不一致。

308
00:13:49,960 --> 00:13:55,520
And it can be one day, two days, a week, two weeks, a month trying to decide what to do.
可能是一天、两天、一周、两周、一个月来试图决定怎么做。

309
00:13:55,520 --> 00:14:01,320
I remember in the OJ Simpson case, the jury took a long time to figure out what they were
我记得在O.J.辛普森案中，陪审团花了很长时间才弄清楚他们

310
00:14:01,320 --> 00:14:02,320
going to do.
要怎么做。

311
00:14:02,320 --> 00:14:04,360
And they said that the jury are common citizens.
而且他们说陪审团是由普通公民组成的。

312
00:14:04,360 --> 00:14:05,360
They're normal people.
他们是普通人。

313
00:14:05,360 --> 00:14:09,880
So what happens in their jobs if they can't go to work because they're doing this?
那如果他们因为做这个而不能去上班，他们的工作怎么办？

314
00:14:09,880 --> 00:14:13,140
Well, in America, this job is called jury duty.
嗯，在美国，这种工作叫陪审义务。

315
00:14:13,140 --> 00:14:17,380
And so someone will send you a letter, and they say, listen, you need to come do jury
所以有人会给你寄一封信，他们说，听着，你需要来履行陪审

316
00:14:17,380 --> 00:14:21,160
duty and you help be a part of the jury.
义务，帮助成为陪审团的一员。

317
00:14:21,160 --> 00:14:26,000
And your job, they can't make you come because this is a service for the government.
而你的工作，他们不能强迫你来，因为这是为政府服务。

318
00:14:26,000 --> 00:14:28,320
So it's above everything else.
所以它高于一切。

319
00:14:28,320 --> 00:14:29,320
It's above.
它高于一切。

320
00:14:29,320 --> 00:14:30,320
You get your normal pay.
你还能拿到正常工资。

321
00:14:30,320 --> 00:14:31,320
There's no problem.
没问题。

322
00:14:31,320 --> 00:14:32,320
But it just don't work.
但就是不管用。

323
00:14:32,320 --> 00:14:33,320
Okay.
好吧。

324
00:14:33,320 --> 00:14:36,720
So they can't fire you if you're in jury duty for like five days or a month or whatever.
所以如果你要当陪审员五天或一个月或更久，他们不能因此解雇你。

325
00:14:36,720 --> 00:14:37,720
No, they can't.
对，他们不能。

326
00:14:37,720 --> 00:14:38,720
That's illegal.
那是违法的。

327
00:14:38,720 --> 00:14:39,720
Wow.
哇。

328
00:14:39,720 --> 00:14:40,720
That's really interesting.
那真有意思。

329
00:14:40,720 --> 00:14:44,000
But a lot of people I've heard don't like to go to jury duty for some reason.
但我听说很多人出于某种原因不喜欢去当陪审员。

330
00:14:44,000 --> 00:14:45,000
Is it tedious?
是因为很枯燥吗？

331
00:14:45,000 --> 00:14:46,240
No, it's probably very boring.
不，可能很无聊。

332
00:14:46,240 --> 00:14:48,520
I've never done it, but it's probably very boring.
我没当过，但可能很无聊。

333
00:14:48,520 --> 00:14:50,080
I would imagine so.
我也这么觉得。

334
00:14:50,080 --> 00:14:51,080
All right.
好了。

335
00:14:51,080 --> 00:14:52,440
Well, that's a very interesting topic.
嗯，这是个很有趣的话题。

336
00:14:52,440 --> 00:14:56,220
I'm sure in your countries, laws are handled differently.
我相信在你们国家，法律处理方式不同。

337
00:14:56,220 --> 00:14:57,580
Maybe you don't have a courtroom.
也许你们没有法庭。

338
00:14:57,580 --> 00:15:00,760
Maybe you have like in England, people wear wigs.
也许像英国那样，人们戴假发。

339
00:15:00,760 --> 00:15:02,400
And black robes.
还有黑袍。

340
00:15:02,400 --> 00:15:05,240
So let us know how it works in your countries.
所以告诉我们你们国家的情况吧。

341
